The overarching goal of this work was to develop tools and methods to build and study complex neuronal net- works controlling the topology of synaptic connexions. Micro-patterning techniques with mechanical and/or chemical constraints were explored regarding their capacity to (i) posi- tion cell bodies, (ii) orient neurite outgrowth and (iii) polarize neurons. This network that mimics the perforant path- way of the hippocampus can be used to study physiological rythms or neurodegenerative processes including Alzheimer’s disease. A novel and fully optical method is presented to stimulate and record neuronal activity in vitro. It opens new routes to study complex cognitive processes in simplified in vitro systems. Because this controlled bacterium will no longer maximize growth, flux balance frameworks are inadequate and instead a kinetic modelling approach is necessary. Given the large number of re- actions included in the network, a pipeline has been built to automatically generate kinetic laws from reaction stoichiometries. In this context a precise description of the reactional mechanism is impossible and I use the convenience kinetic framework for reversible reaction or Michaelis-Menten for irreversible ones; both are derived assuming independent reactants. The parameter fitting searches for the model that matches best the steady state conditions of concentration and flux, prior distributions for parame- ters built from literature data, and time course data for tracers. Experience: [{'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 10, 'year': 2016}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 10, 'year': 2019}, 'company': 'Université de Paris', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/company/universit%C3%A9-paris-cit%C3%A9', 'title': 'PHD Graduate Student', 'description': 'Colour change is not as unusual as often thought. Although the mechanisms allowing colour change are currently largely understood, the evolution of this intriguing ability remains poorly investigated. In chameleons, there is some support for the “selection for social signalling” hypothesis. However, in chameleons, one prediction which states that there should be “More intense sexual selection” remains to be tested. Moreover, the evolution of chameleon colour change has only been investigated at the genus level while the entire family is capable of changing colour. The aims of this thesis are to better understand the evolution of colour change and the evolution thereof. I approach this topic through two main lines of research. First, I investigated the role of colour change in sexual selection in the panther chameleon through an integrative approach combining physiological and performance measurements, behavioural experiments, and colour analysis. Second, I studied the evolution of colour change within Chamaeleonidae. I traced the evolution of colour change using a comparative phylogenetic analysis and explored some of the selective pressures thought to have driven its evolution.', 'location': 'Paris, France', Fellowship from the France Stanford Center for Interdisciplinary Studies', 'location': 'Palo Alto', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C560BAQHr9suxyJBXMw/company-logo_100_100/0/1635534378574?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=585atWEpeS1nLPOjTMFmVwhzraXbAVDB5RFXNzX6jiM'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 10, 'year': 2011}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 7, 'year': 2015}, 'company': 'CNRS', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/company/cnrs', 'title': 'PHD in Mathematical Biology', 'description': 'We propose in this thesis to characterize variability quantitatively at various scales during embryogenesis. We use a combination of mathematical models and experimental results

In the first part, we use a small cohort of digital sea urchin embryos to construct a prototypical representation of the cell lineage, which relates individual cell features with embryo-level dynamics. This multi-level data-driven probabilistic model relies on symmetries of the embryo and known cell types, which provide a generic coarse-grained level of observation for distributions of individual cell features. The prototype is defined as the centroid of the cohort in the corresponding statistical manifold. Among several results, we show that intra-individual variability is involved in the reproducibility of the developmental process.

In the second part, we consider the mechanisms sources of variability during development and their relations to evolution. Building on experimental results showing variable phenotypic expression and incomplete penetrance in a zebrafish mutant line, we propose a clarification of the various levels of biological variability using a formal analogy with quantum mechanics mathematical framework. Surprisingly, we find a formal analogy between quantum entanglement and Mendel’s idealized scheme of inheritance.

In the third part, we study biological organization and its relations to developmental paths. By adapting the tools of algebraic topology, we compute invariants of the network of cellular contacts extracted from confocal microscopy images of epithelia from different species and genetic backgrounds. In particular, we show the influence of individual histories on the spatial distribution of cells in epithelial tissues.', 'location': 'Région de Paris, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4D0BAQEFt4peFzbeug/company-logo_100_100/0/1547216942284?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=cGWRvq6SwOLAbJNjfJFp3xyMCqAK0FV5VlA0v7vHFvM'}]

A la croisée des mondes de la recherche, de l'entreprenariat et de la société, DRISS (Digital Research in Science & Society) crée les synergies pour révéler et mobiliser le meilleur du potentiel numérique et humain de vos organisations. 

Nos actions : 
- Des formations modulaires et ancrées dans des immersions pratiques (apprentissage et acculturation par le "faire", développement de compétences techniques, méthodologiques et réflexives pour gagner en autonomie ) 
- Du conseil stratégique, organisationnel et technique : développement du potentiel humain et collectif (méthodologie agile et participative), maitrise des enjeux éthiques et juridiques numériques (RGPD, DPI et open), élaboration d'environnement numérique adapté à l'open et data science)
- Développement et assistance à maitrise d'ouvrage logiciels open source.

Context: Thanks to recent advances in electronics and materials science, electroencephalography (EEG) is becoming available to the general public, for both health and entertainment purposes. However, the inter- and intra-individual variability of brain signals poses a challenge to develop applications that may be used in everyday life. Problematic: Most current EEG applications are built on sessions preceded by a calibration step used to train a classifier. I investigated here the potential of online semi- supervised machine learning methods to shorten the calibration phase by using the data generated during the session to continuously train the classifier. I focused specifically on EEG emotional gaming applications.
Methods: Eight subjects were recorded using a 8-electrodes EEG headset while viewing images annotated with emotional states. An online active semi-supervised learning algorithm was trained and tested on each subject’s data, using eleven features descriptive of the emotional state. The results were compared with those of a standard Support Vector Machine model.
Results: None of those algorithms was more accurate than a random classification. Education: [{'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2012}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 12, 'year': 2015}, 'field_of_study': 'Physics, Chemistry, Biology', 'degree_name': "Diplôme d'ingénieur", 'school': 'ESPCI Paris', 'school_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/school/espci/', 'description': 'An ESPCI Paris education takes place over four years. The first two years are designed to be interdisciplinary and, through common core classes, give students a solid foundation in biology, chemistry, physics, mathematics, economics, computer science and language. Practical work is an important part of these classes. In their third year, student-engineers choose a specialty: physics, chemistry, physical chemistry or biotechnology. A six-month industry internship also starts the third year, followed by four months of specialized classes and a two-to three-month lab-based research project. Students have many choices in their fourth year, which may be spent in France or abroad: a masters degree, specialized masters degree, double diploma, and graduate school (IFP School, INSTN) are all possible. Two out of three graduates continue their education with a doctoral thesis, which takes three years and in one out of five cases, is carried out abroad.', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQEceP1ZHeVfJw/company-logo_100_100/0/1519910434485?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=1NoD6AJdMSMDPvQu6NCc0EDSITTMzWH0oLqO17to8hc'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2015}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 12, 'year': 2016}, 'field_of_study': 'Biology', 'degree_name': 'Master of Science', 'school': 'Centre de Recherches Interdisciplinaires', 'school_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/school/learningplanetinstitute/', 'description': 'The Interdisciplinary Approaches in Life Sciences (AIV) Master (M.Sc) of Paris Diderot and Descartes universities is an interdisciplinary two-year program tackling quantitative approaches on different interfaces with Life Sciences. It aims at training creative and talented students to develop their research  in an environment as enriching as the best world graduate programs. The program is based on learning through research pedagogy – rich with research internships and collaborative projects.\nDuring the second year students deepen their knowledge of life sciences, develop their ability to critically analyze scientific works and discover the Research world. The M2 curriculum is devoted to research, through three internships, with at least one theoretical internship and one experimental internship. Intimately linked to research, teaching will cultivate new forms of pedagogy, particularly in order to “learn how to learn,” right from the bachelor’s degree and on throughout life. ► ABOUT ADAPTATION

The project ADAPTATION aims at understanding how individuals leaving their regular life environment adapt during four weeks in environmental conditions that are physically, emotionally and socially extremely challenging. By taking part into four 1-month expeditions, 20 subjects (10 women & 10 men) will trek in four locations considered as the most extreme for human beings in terms of both isolation and physical conditions (the Dasht-e-Lut desert in Iran, the deep Amazonian forest, the Verkhoyansk mounts in Northern oriental Siberia, and the Tierra del Fuego in south Patagonia).

http://2014.igem.org/Team:Paris_Bettencourt

"Body odor is caused by the metabolic action of bacteria on human sweat. Existing deodorants are antibiotic - they kill all skin bacteria including neutral and beneficial species. Where body odor carries a social stigma, alternatives to deodorant are few.

The iGEM Paris Bettencourt 2014 project explores new ways to control body odors through precise modifications of the living microbiome. We target common odors of the armpit and foot, as well as odors specific to old age or genetic disease. We present a BioBrick smell library for mixing genetic perfumes and a CRISPR-mediated technology for isolating naturally odorless bacterial strains."', 'location': 'Paris Area, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHm2klwM0guAg/company-logo_100_100/0/1640079045078?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=wizOFhOLyAmDmibMAp9H6Xc8cz6NybOe-W-Un6UyzwE'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2013}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 12, 'year': 2014}, 'company': 'CRI - Centre de Recherches Interdisciplinaires', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/learningplanetinstitute', 'title': 'Science Teacher', 'description': 'Practical course in Genetics, Bachelor level', 'location': 'Paris Area, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHm2klwM0guAg/company-logo_100_100/0/1640079045078?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=wizOFhOLyAmDmibMAp9H6Xc8cz6NybOe-W-Un6UyzwE'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2013}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 11, 'year': 2013}, 'company': 'CRI - Centre de Recherches Interdisciplinaires', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/learningplanetinstitute', 'title': 'Mentor of the iGEM Paris Bettencourt 2013 team', 'description': 'Infectious Disease Control project "Fight Tuberculosis with Modern Weapons"
(Grand Prize winner and Best Health & Medicine Project award)

http://2013.igem.org/Team:Paris_Bettencourt

"To defeat tuberculosis, we need new biotechnology. Our work adds 4 new tools to the anti-TB medical armamentarium. Detect - a CRISPR-based biosensor delivered by phage and sequence-specific for antibiotic resistance. Target - an E. coli model hosting an essential mycobacterial metabolic pathway that could simplify drug screening. Infiltrate - an E. coli strain capable of entering infected macrophages and lysing mycobacteria. Sabotage - a non-lytic phage that spreads horizontally in a bacterial population and expresses an siRNA to knock down antibiotic resistance."', 'location': 'Paris Area, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHm2klwM0guAg/company-logo_100_100/0/1640079045078?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=wizOFhOLyAmDmibMAp9H6Xc8cz6NybOe-W-Un6UyzwE'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2012}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 11, 'year': 2012}, 'company': 'CRI - Centre de Recherches Interdisciplinaires', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/learningplanetinstitute', 'title': 'Student member of the iGEM Paris Bettencourt 2012 team', 'description': 'Genetically Engineered Organisms Containment project "bWARE: How safe is safe enough?"
(2nd Runner-up overall and Best Environment Project award)

http://2012.igem.org/Team:Paris_Bettencourt

"Synthetic biologists, and iGEM teams in particular, design Genetically Engineered Organisms (GEOs) to benefit people and communities around the world. However, many proposed applications necessarily involve the deployment of GEOs in natural environments. These dreams can never be made real without technical, legal and ethical guidelines for the use of GEOs outside the lab. Our project addresses this serious need from our perspective as safety bioengineers, citizens and humans. 

We have developed the bWARE containment module to substantially reduce the risk of Horizontal Gene Trasfer (HGT) while remaining compatible with existing iGEM devices. A GEO may first perform its beneficial function during a programmed delay. Then our system activates, irreversibly degrading DNA throughout the population, leaving no genetic information behind. Multiple cooperative systems provide redundancy against inevitable mutations or external stresses."', 'location': 'Paris Area, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHm2klwM0guAg/company-logo_100_100/0/1640079045078?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=wizOFhOLyAmDmibMAp9H6Xc8cz6NybOe-W-Un6UyzwE'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 3, 'year': 2011}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 6, 'year': 2011}, 'company': 'University of Zagreb, Faculty of Science', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/university-of-zagreb-faculty-of-science', 'title': 'Student Internship', 'description': 'Molecular Biology project "Detection and Molecular Characterization of Phytoplasma in Species Vitis Vinifera"', 'location': 'Zagreb, Croatia', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHQwQP1n7ps_w/company-logo_100_100/0/1600673293940?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=AwzTNSL4AWoKk5IbCTzLN6RfmSP8OXtHeQEMxz48weY'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 3, 'year': 2008}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 6, 'year': 2008}, 'company': 'University of Zagreb, Faculty of Science', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://www.linkedin.com/company/university-of-zagreb-faculty-of-science', 'title': 'Student Internship', 'description': 'Proteome Analysis project "Proteome Analysis of Sugar Beet Tissue Lines"', 'location': 'Zagreb, Croatia', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C4E0BAQHQwQP1n7ps_w/company-logo_100_100/0/1600673293940?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=AwzTNSL4AWoKk5IbCTzLN6RfmSP8OXtHeQEMxz48weY'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 10, 'year': 2007}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 8, 'year': 2008}, 'company': 'Ilirika Consulting Ltd.', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': None, 'title': 'Assistant to Director', 'description': 'Investment consulting', 'location': 'Zagreb, Croatia', 'logo_url': None}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2005}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 12, 'year': 2006}, 'company': 'V.B.Z. [{'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 1, 'year': 2017}, 'ends_at': None, 'company': 'Collège de France', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/company/coll%C3%A8gedefrance', 'title': 'PhD candidate', 'description': 'Antibodies are major players of the immune response.  Their interest lies in their very specific affinity against pathogenic antigens.  This affinity increases by an accelerated evolutionary process known as affinity maturation, which consists in iterative rounds of mutation and selection.  Many antibodies, however, are polyreactive:  they bind to antigens unrelated to those for which they are selected.  This property is hypothesized to contribute to their evolvability – their capacity to increase their affinity through evolution – but is also responsible for autoimmune responses and limits the development of therapeutic antibodies. My project aims at characterizing the evolution of polyreactivity during affinity maturation. I propose an innovative and quantitative approach that combines in vitro experiments of directed evolution and analysis of high-throughput sequencing data based on statistical analysis tools to investigate polyreactivity.', 'location': 'Région de Paris, France', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C560BAQFcQ6_FLTG7wQ/company-logo_100_100/0/1519882463495?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=jVeEDCOJmvckUQXV8yfObAE1HU9SRYixTZZUKr3nkB4'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 12, 'year': 2016}, 'ends_at': {'day': 31, 'month': 5, 'year': 2017}, 'company': 'Artificial chromosome engineering', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/company/institut-pasteur', 'title': 'Visiting Research Fellow at the Pasteur Institute', 'description': None, 'location': 'Koszul Lab', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C560BAQH2Hq1M1jR8IQ/company-logo_100_100/0/1583233227775?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=uY-ATY6fNgTSvtV2YB8Noarp6fYHEbXcco2cI8EHl6g'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 3, 'year': 2016}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 9, 'year': 2016}, 'company': 'Visiting Researcher at Harvard Medical School', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': 'https://fr.linkedin.com/company/harvard-medical-school', 'title': 'Visiting Researcher at Harvard Medical School', 'description': 'This project aims at the control of gene expression in a completely innovative way via the implementation of logic gates in genetic circuits. The deregulation of iron homeostasis due to gene defects or environmental stresses leads to a wide range of diseases with consequences for cellular metabolism that remain poorly understood. The modelling of iron homeostasis in relation to the main features of metabolism, energy production and oxidative stress may provide new clues to the ways in which changes in biological processes in a normal cell lead to disease.

Using a methodology based on probabilistic Boolean modeling, I am in charge of constructing the first model of human iron homeostasis including oxygen-related reactions in the frame of central metabolism.', 'location': 'Henri Mondor hospital', 'logo_url': None}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 9, 'year': 2014}, 'ends_at': {'day': 30, 'month': 6, 'year': 2015}, 'company': 'Next Generation Sequencing', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': None, 'title': 'Student Project', 'description': 'Genetic diseases diagnostics are becoming efficient as well as accessible due to Next Generation Se-quencing technologies. Abstract: 
Diatoms are unicellular photosynthetic microeukaryotes that play a critical role in the functioning of marine ecosystems. They are responsible for 20% of global photosynthesis on Earth and lie at the base of marine food webs, ever more threatened by climate change.
Diatoms establish microbial interactions with numerous organisms across the whole tree of life, through complex mechanisms including symbiosis, parasitism and competition. The goal of my thesis was to understand how those biotic interactions structure the planktonic community at large spatial scales, by using new approaches based on the unprecedented Tara Oceans dataset, a unique and worldwide circumnavigation that collected over 40.000 samples across 210 sites to explore the diversity and functions of marine microbes. 
Through the analysis of microbial association networks, I show that diatoms act as repulsive segregators in the ocean, in particular towards potentially harmful organisms such as predators as well as parasites, and that species co-occurrence is driven by environmental factors in a minority of cases. By leveraging the singularity of the Tara Oceans data, I provide a comprehensive characterization of a prevalent biotic interaction between a diatom and heterotrophic ciliates at large spatial scale, illustrating the success of data-driven research. Overall, my thesis contributes to our understanding of diatom biotic interactions, from the global patterns to the single cell.

Our objectives was helping people not to rely on donations anymore but seizing opportunities with their own hands.

How ?
By giving them confidence that they themselves can have ideas and solutions and do not have to wait for others.
By giving them tools for discussion and co-construction.
By giving entrepreneurs crash courses on business analysis, strategic marketing, pitches and "what else is out there"

Methods for collaborative sessions (up to 100 villagers)
Icebreaker, How do you want your life to be in 5 years (education/work, healthcare, transportation, relation with the mayor, housing), Vote on the popular ideas (with beans !), Open discussions on how to reach this ideal (project managers, transition, using governments and NPOs help).

Methods for Impact Consulting (entrepreneurs and non-profit) :
Strategy: Revenue-Cost analysis, Porter's 5 forces, SAVE framework, analysis of donors market
Pitch sessions

We helped:
- 3 entrepreneurs,
- 2 villages of 1000 people by working with 50 and 100 during open innovation sessions
- Fofaja, a center for blind children who lost all funding in 2015 which supported 30 workers and 100 blind children
- an orphanage

Results :
- Among 3 sources of revenues, one innkeeper targeted the most promising one for breakeven in 7 years.
- One hat maker will drop her current buyers to focus on selling her luxury handcrafted hat through Internet and fair trade buyers
- Fofaja will work on their promotion across Africa (they have the sole Braille printer in Madagascar by the way) and a collaboration with Habaka, an innovation hub led to a 3-day Hackathon on Oct 14 to build www.fofaja.org
- Anjoma-Betoho, a rural village build a basketball field in 15 days to welcome the regional high school competition and the Ministry of Sport (hopefully getting more support).

Dengue is a mosquito-borne infection affecting tropical and subtropical regions
around the world. Approximately 40% of the world's population (2.5 billion people), in over
100 countries is at risk of infection by the dengue virus (DENV) [1]. The main problem being
to determine which patients will develop a severe, potentially deadly form of Dengue [2]; the
molecular processes behind the different forms are not well known and there is a great need
to investigate them in order to develop vaccines and diagnostic tests.
The partner team of Anavaj SAKUNTABHAI in Institute Pasteur discovered that a
lipoprotein plays an important role in the difference between the most severe class of dengue
disease and other classes (unpublished data). The systems biology team of Benno
SCHWIKOWSKI developed a novel classifier based on isotonic regression [3].
Our objective is to find a biomarker or biomarker pairs, that together with this
lipoprotein level will allow to distinguish the group of most severe patients. The goal of the
research is to build a predictive model that will enable the correct classification of patients
between these severity groups based on the transcriptome data. It will also unveil
transcriptome pairs highly correlated with the disease different stages. Importantly, protein
names and associated prior knowledge are not used. Thus, our analysis may lead to
discovery and further validation of novel biomarkers.", 'location': 'Paris, 75016', 'logo_url': 'https://media-exp1.licdn.com/dms/image/C560BAQH2Hq1M1jR8IQ/company-logo_100_100/0/1583233227775?e=1660176000&v=beta&t=uY-ATY6fNgTSvtV2YB8Noarp6fYHEbXcco2cI8EHl6g'}, {'starts_at': {'day': 1, 'month': 7, 'year': 2016}, 'ends_at': {'day': 28, 'month': 2, 'year': 2017}, 'company': 'PLOS', 'company_linkedin_profile_url': None, 'title': 'Senior Blogger', 'description': 'Blogging for PLOS computational Biology
